00:15:06,878 --> 00:15:10,201
And stop talking about the wind, because this has now

283
00:15:10,241 --> 00:15:11,903
become much more important.

284
00:15:13,914 --> 00:15:17,257
We have to interrupt the dialogue naturally, and that's like really scary to do.

285
00:15:18,778 --> 00:15:23,062
So it means that I, it actually means things for how I write the dialogue.

286
00:15:23,742 --> 00:15:27,345
It means I can't write super lengthy lines that we need to finish in order to be interrupted

287
00:15:27,365 --> 00:15:28,146
in natural fashion.

288
00:15:28,166 --> 00:15:32,469
I need to be able to time the new dialogue to interrupt in concordance with the thing

289
00:15:32,489 --> 00:15:33,510
that the player has just found.

290
00:15:35,172 --> 00:15:37,754
Or if it's even just like on screen, whatever event has triggered that.

291
00:15:39,362 --> 00:15:44,165
We need all the dialogue to exist in an organized and discrete chunk so it can be rearranged.

292
00:15:44,705 --> 00:15:47,827
The speech manager needs to know exactly what's happening in the game at all times.

293
00:15:48,487 --> 00:15:51,269
And sometimes the cone of the conversation actually needs to change.

294
00:15:53,110 --> 00:15:53,231
So...

295
00:15:54,538 --> 00:15:57,659
Like, I have to write short, snappy, back-and-forth dialogue,

296
00:15:57,719 --> 00:16:01,040
and I have to save longer monologues for times when I know stuff can't happen,

297
00:16:01,060 --> 00:16:01,861
which is super rare.

298
00:16:02,521 --> 00:16:04,621
And then I actually voice direct lines in tight concordance

299
00:16:04,641 --> 00:16:06,822
with the possible, like, tones of the story,

300
00:16:07,002 --> 00:16:08,483
sometimes duplicating conversations,

301
00:16:09,103 --> 00:16:10,243
pre- and post-a-specific event.

302
00:16:11,784 --> 00:16:13,944
But the thing that allows any of this to work

303
00:16:13,964 --> 00:16:16,185
is the system and methodologies used to organize

304
00:16:16,905 --> 00:16:17,785
the written content of the game.

305
00:16:19,578 --> 00:16:22,879
So we actually took major cues from Elon Ruskin's 2012 GDC talk

306
00:16:23,500 --> 00:16:24,760
about Val's dialogue system.

307
00:16:25,260 --> 00:16:27,621
There are aspects of it that don't quite work for our game

308
00:16:27,662 --> 00:16:29,582
because it's really dialogue choice heavy.

309
00:16:29,602 --> 00:16:33,324
Excuse me, but the principles he outlines in the talk

310
00:16:33,704 --> 00:16:35,365
are like, which is available outside of the vault.

311
00:16:35,385 --> 00:16:36,125
You can just go find it.

312
00:16:36,145 --> 00:16:39,687
They've been like an invaluable cornerstone

313
00:16:39,987 --> 00:16:41,228
to the thing that we're trying to build.

314
00:16:42,548 --> 00:16:43,849
So yeah, I'll share with you where we're at

315
00:16:43,869 --> 00:16:44,909
and the problems we're considering

316
00:16:44,929 --> 00:16:46,670
and some of the ways we're thinking about solving them.

317
00:16:48,151 --> 00:16:51,213
To really oversimplify the process, you should just really go watch the talk.

318
00:16:52,014 --> 00:16:54,756
Each of the lines is triggered by a singular event

319
00:16:55,156 --> 00:16:59,599
and is aware via appropriate context at what point in the game it's allowed to be triggered.

320
00:17:00,140 --> 00:17:04,503
The dialogue system and the event manager work together to find the most pertinent line in the database

321
00:17:05,003 --> 00:17:07,085
and deliver it to the player at the most appropriate time.

322
00:17:09,109 --> 00:17:11,411
So we want to vary user-friendly.

323
00:17:11,431 --> 00:17:14,274
Because I guess I'm the user and I'm an idiot.

324
00:17:14,414 --> 00:17:16,255
So I need to have a very user-friendly way

325
00:17:16,295 --> 00:17:19,138
to generate and organize dialogue contents and story

326
00:17:19,158 --> 00:17:19,418
moments.

327
00:17:20,199 --> 00:17:22,061
Because Firewatch is not procedural.

328
00:17:23,242 --> 00:17:25,443
It's more systems-driven than some of the things

329
00:17:25,524 --> 00:17:26,204
we've ever worked on.

330
00:17:26,404 --> 00:17:29,027
But it's not procedural at all.

331
00:17:29,067 --> 00:17:29,827
It's not a puzzle game.

332
00:17:29,867 --> 00:17:31,729
Like, content isn't being generated by a robot.

333
00:17:32,750 --> 00:17:33,891
The game is going to rely on lots of.

334
00:17:34,802 --> 00:17:37,683
Responsive content succeed, and we're a super small team,

335
00:17:37,823 --> 00:17:40,444
so we have to be able to generate that and implement it really quickly.

336
00:17:40,464 --> 00:17:42,725
And we've established goals for how I write,

337
00:17:43,085 --> 00:17:44,566
and now we're developing this tool to help me get there.

338
00:17:45,846 --> 00:17:48,727
For now, I work in a relatively free-form way,

339
00:17:49,227 --> 00:17:50,808
and then chop up the individual lines

340
00:17:52,068 --> 00:17:53,008
so they can be put into a database.

341
00:17:53,609 --> 00:17:56,650
And right now, Patrick Ewing, who's a programmer we're working with at Campo Santo,

342
00:17:56,670 --> 00:17:59,131
and I are trying to flatten the process

343
00:18:00,651 --> 00:18:03,692
from written dialogue line to implementation in a database into the game.

344
00:18:04,746 --> 00:18:07,467
So to put it as simply as possible, we're trying to consider

345
00:18:07,487 --> 00:18:10,788
what are the fewest amounts of button presses it takes

346
00:18:11,248 --> 00:18:14,249
to write a line, store all of its logic and data,

347
00:18:14,789 --> 00:18:17,089
record it, implement it, and tinker with the timing

348
00:18:17,129 --> 00:18:17,990
to ship in the final game.

349
00:18:18,630 --> 00:18:20,550
We're trying to solve this really complex problem

350
00:18:21,030 --> 00:18:23,131
which is compounded by a realization that we both had

351
00:18:23,891 --> 00:18:27,052
which is how these tools work is gonna dictate

352
00:18:28,032 --> 00:18:29,973
what comes out of the screen, not just the pipeline.

353
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:35,604
It means fundamental things to the nature of the game's cadence and tone, the dialogue itself.

354
00:18:36,585 --> 00:18:39,587
So if we're going to choose to develop a system predicated on world state

355
00:18:40,288 --> 00:18:43,751
and the possibility of interruption and to respond to lots of different player inputs

356
00:18:44,011 --> 00:18:47,894
and the content we feed that system, the actual writing has to be compatible.

357
00:18:48,515 --> 00:18:52,098
Every choice we make about how the tool works alongside the game's systems

358
00:18:52,418 --> 00:18:54,540
impacts what we're able to put into the system

359
00:18:55,140 --> 00:18:56,661
and therefore what we're able to push out of the screen.

360
00:18:57,839 --> 00:19:01,281
Because it's worth, like again, we need to make as much of it as possible.

361
00:19:01,901 --> 00:19:05,143
In this game you're going to be talking to someone over a radio as you explore.

362
00:19:05,163 --> 00:19:10,526
In most games, when you write dialogue, you know a character is going to be in a certain place at a certain time.

363
00:19:10,787 --> 00:19:13,168
You literally bring a character with you anywhere.

364
00:19:13,808 --> 00:19:15,029
So the dialogue has to reflect that.

365
00:19:15,449 --> 00:19:18,151
And to do that, we need like, just a shitload of it.

366
00:19:20,143 --> 00:19:24,386
So we struggle to consider flexibility against agility.

367
00:19:24,726 --> 00:19:27,687
How feature-rich do we make the front end of a tool

368
00:19:27,727 --> 00:19:30,469
versus how good is it at making the exact game we're

369
00:19:30,489 --> 00:19:31,089
trying to make?

370
00:19:31,629 --> 00:19:33,370
We err towards the latter, obviously.

371
00:19:33,890 --> 00:19:35,431
We need to make this one game.

372
00:19:35,931 --> 00:19:38,353
But it's an inescapable lure to think, well, what if the

373
00:19:38,393 --> 00:19:38,993
tool could?

374
00:19:39,493 --> 00:19:40,594
It doesn't just take time to build.

375
00:19:41,514 --> 00:19:45,496
But that moment of wondering, well, what if the tool also

376
00:19:45,536 --> 00:19:48,578
let us, is going to impact the game we make, the actual

377
00:19:48,618 --> 00:19:48,918
content.

378
00:19:50,383 --> 00:19:52,925
If you give a craftsperson a brush versus a pencil,

379
00:19:52,945 --> 00:19:54,506
you're going to get two very different images.

380
00:19:55,067 --> 00:19:56,107
And at the most basic level,

381
00:19:57,188 --> 00:19:58,089
all we really need to do

382
00:19:58,729 --> 00:20:01,992
is write down and store a bunch of data in a database.

383
00:20:02,452 --> 00:20:03,633
It's like we could easily use Excel.

384
00:20:03,653 --> 00:20:06,254
We could just organize a bunch of lines

385
00:20:06,855 --> 00:20:07,655
as individual events.

386
00:20:07,675 --> 00:20:09,357
So when the player does X,

387
00:20:09,917 --> 00:20:11,778
or world state is Y, we just make thing happen.

388
00:20:14,299 --> 00:20:17,842
So, what we've settled on thus far is creating a very simple interface

389
00:20:18,242 --> 00:20:20,665
that has as much searchability as possible.

390
00:20:21,365 --> 00:20:24,909
Because we want to be able to look at a line in a tool and give it a bunch of new requirements on the fly.

391
00:20:25,730 --> 00:20:29,113
Requirements is the stuff that says, oh, I can happen when this is true.

392
00:20:29,834 --> 00:20:33,717
Furthermore, we know we can take a big bite out of the polishing phase of the game.

393
00:20:34,298 --> 00:20:37,301
So it would be amazing if we could actually tune the timing of the dialogue right in the tool.

394
00:20:38,983 --> 00:20:40,924
I focus on a couple of core features like this.

395
00:20:40,944 --> 00:20:44,268
It's going to help us debug quickly and shift the dialogue faster.

396
00:20:45,809 --> 00:20:49,252
But I want to point out that decisions to create and deliver content in a certain way,

397
00:20:49,573 --> 00:20:53,417
to build a certain tool, actually help us combat the hurdles that stand in the way to

398
00:20:53,457 --> 00:20:55,599
creating suspension of disbelief that I mentioned before.

399
00:20:56,600 --> 00:20:58,962
Long cutscenes start to go away because of our methodology.

400
00:20:59,622 --> 00:21:01,785
Bad dialogue timing can hopefully be solved right in the tool.

401
00:21:02,777 --> 00:21:04,419
We can respond to player choice more deftly,

402
00:21:04,439 --> 00:21:06,541
and we're trying to flatten the content pipeline.

403
00:21:07,022 --> 00:21:09,965
The same goes for interactions, story, and cutscene density.

